			<section>
				<h2>Why Use The Training Room At All?</h2>
				<p>
					Because you suck. You don't win your matches. You have a win rate
					that is frankly embarassing. Every round you play, you think. You
					take the time to devise a strategy. You've played a lot and you can
					do your combos >90% of the time. You don't usually screw up your
					punishes when the opportunity comes and you have ideas on how to
					approach most matchups. 
				</p>
				<p>
					<b>But you still suck.</b>
				</p>
				<p>
					You have no footsies. You have no foresight. You haven't developed
					your godlike <em>Yomi</em> to the point where you are forcing the
					course of your matches. You feel confident but you have no actual
					confidence. You don't know what your opponent is doing or how to
					force your opponent to do the things you know he or she is going
					to do. You <em>are</em> fooling yourself.
				</p>
				<p>
					<b>That is what the Training Room is for.</b>
				</p>
			</section>
			<section>
				<h2>Hear Me Out!</h2>
				<p>
					I know that it sounds weird to say that in order to better approach
					your opponents and every matchup in the game you need to spend many
					hours playing against a static unmoving dummy in training mode. But 
					the time you spend in training will yield dividends far beyond what
					hours of online warrior throwdowns ever could.
				</p>
				<p>
					The next level is to not only have a vague idea of what you should
					do in any given situation-- it is not even knowing what the optimal
					response or next move in any situation is as objective fact. It is
					so much less about <em>knowing</em> and far more about putting in
					your reps. There is nothing more valuable for a player who loses in
					quick thinking situations than to repeatedly put yourself in that 
					situation and practice your response. You can explore the value of
					multiple responses for whichever opponenet or situation you are in.
				</p>
