				<p>
					If you've had Vega hit the wall and fly at you with his claws opening
					on you from in front and behind a hundred times you'll know exactly
					what moves you have that beat him out. Furthermore you'll have a 
					deep comprehension of the timing, spacing and inputs necessary to
					consistently demolish your opponent. Your brain won't waste time
					deciding what commands to send to your wrists and fingers, rather, it
					will respond to the game like Floyd Mayweather to an incoming jab. 
					When you've committed actions and responses to memory on that
					level you won't find yourself losing to situations like these.
				</p>
			</section>
			<section>
				<h2>Death By A Thousand Papercuts | Armor Between Your Fingers</h2>
				<p>
					Lets say your opponent has a move that does 2% damage but every time
					it is attempted against you, you fail to defend or counter it. So
					when your opponent approaches you and establishes their proper
					spacing, they will do a guaranteed 2% damage to you. It takes 50 of
					these attacks to kill you in a round. You could view this how many
					new players to Street Fighter games view fireballs. When you are
					put into a situation where you have no immediate, memory-baked
					response to your opponent you are far more likely to lose. You can
					know exactly what you should do to defeat the opposing strategy
					but you are unable to do this. <em>This is what you work on in
						the training room</em>
				</p>
